int:\n        def dfs(node, dist, visited):\n            if visited[node] != -1:\n                # Cycle detected\n                return dist - visited[node]\n            if edges[node] == -1:\n                # No outgoing edge\n                return -1\n            \n            visited[node] = dist\n            cycle_length = dfs(edges[node], dist + 1, visited)\n            visited[node] = -1  # Backtrack to allow other cycles to use this node\n            \n            return cycle_length\n        \n        n = len(edges)\n        visited = [-1] * n\n        max_cycle = -1\n        \n        for i in range(n):\n            if visited[i] == -1:\n                max_cycle = max(max_cycle, dfs(i, 0, visited))\n        \n        return max_cycle\n```\n\nThis solution uses a depth-first search (DFS) approach to detect cycles in the graph. It keeps track of the distance from the starting node to each node using the `visited` array. If a node is revisited, a cycle is detected, and the length of the cycle is calculated. The solution iterates through all nodes to ensure all components of the graph are checked. If no cycle is found, it returns -1.", "estimated_date": 1659225600000}